aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Report for Piper PA 28-181 in Strasburg, Colorado
The accident occurred in Strasburg, Colorado.
The accident occurred on November 20, 2014, at 20:40 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Piper PA 28-181.
The defining event of the accident was fuel exhaustion.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Instructional.
The accident number was CEN15CA055.
The aircraft registration was N2204Q.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
The accident resulted in 1 minor injury and 1 person uninjured.
The flight was a visual flight rules night flight.
The pilot estimated the airplane had about 30 to 32 gallons of fuel before departure.
The flight departed from Rocky Mountain Metropolitan Airport in Denver, Colorado.
Rocky Mountain Metropolitan Airport's identifier is BJC.
The departure time was approximately 1825 MST.
During the flight, the aircraft experienced intermittent electrical issues.
The electrical issues included static in the headsets.
The electrical issues included flickering instrument panel lights.
The electrical issues included a fluctuating ammeter gauge.
Attempts to resolve the electrical issues were unsuccessful.
The aircraft made a touch and go landing at Kit Carson Airport in Burlington, Colorado.
Kit Carson Airport's identifier is ITR.
After the touch and go landing, a decision was made to shorten the flight.
The pilot decided to return to Rocky Mountain Metropolitan Airport.
The fuel gauges indicated about 8 gallons remaining in each fuel tank at Kit Carson Airport.
Twenty minutes after departing Kit Carson Airport, the fuel gauges showed empty.
At approximately 2035 MST, the engine stopped producing power.
The pilot switched to the opposite fuel tank when the engine stopped.
The engine restarted after switching fuel tanks.
The flight continued for about 4 to 5 more minutes after the engine restart.
The engine stopped producing power a second time.
During the forced landing attempt, the airplane struck wires.
After striking wires, the airplane impacted the ground.
The pilot and flight instructor stated the airplane's fuel load should have been sufficient for a flight of about 3 hours.
The total duration of the accident flight was about 2.25 hours.
Examination of the airplane after the accident revealed no fuel remaining in either wing tank.
There was no evidence of a fuel spill at the accident site.
No pre-impact anomalies were found with the airplane's fuel system.
The pilot reported the accident could have been prevented by ordering more fuel before departure.
The pilot reported the accident could have been prevented by obtaining fuel at Kit Carson Airport.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Strasburg, Colorado

## Date & Time: 
November 20, 2014, 20:40 Local

## Aircraft:
Piper PA 28-181

## Defining Event:
Fuel exhaustion

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Instructional

## Accident Number:
CEN15CA055

## Registration:
N2204Q

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 Minor, 1 None

## Analysis

The pilot reported that the airplane was operated on a visual flight rules night flight. He estimated that the airplane had about 30 to 32 gallons of fuel prior to departure from the Rocky Mountain Metropolitan Airport (BJC), Denver, Colorado, about 1825 mst. During the flight, intermittent electrical issues were experienced including static in the headsets, flickering instrument panel lights and a fluctuating ammeter gauge. Attempts were made to alleviate the electrical issues to no avail. A touch and go landing was made at the Kit Carson Airport (ITR), Burlington, Colorado, and a decision was made to shorten the flight and return to the departure airport. The pilot reported that the fuel gauges indicated that the airplane had about 8 gallons remaining in each fuel tank about his time. After 20 minutes had elapsed from the departure from ITR, the fuel gauges showed empty. About 2035 mst, the engine stopped producing power and the pilot switched to the opposite fuel tank. The engine restarted and the flight continued for about 4 to 5 more minutes when the engine again stopped producing power. During the forced landing attempt the airplane struck wires and subsequently impacted the ground. The pilot and the flight instructor stated that the airplane's fuel load prior to departure should have been sufficient for a flight of about 3 hours. The total duration of the accident flight was about 2.25 hours. Examination of the airplane subsequent to the accident revealed no fuel remaining in either wing tank. There was no evidence of a fuel spill and no preimpact anomalies were found with respect to the airplane's fuel system. The pilot reported that the accident could have been prevented by ordering more fuel prior to departure or obtaining fuel at ITR.
